The V-12 program served as a launching pad for a remarkable array of individuals who would go on to achieve significant prominence in various fields. These alumni demonstrate the program's far-reaching impact beyond its immediate military objectives.

*   [George Allen](/George_Allen_(American_football_coach)), a distinguished [football coach](/American_football), honed his skills at [Alma College](/Alma_College) and [Marquette University](/Marquette_University).
*   [Howard Baker](/Howard_Baker), who later became a [U.S. Senator](/U.S._Senator) from [Tennessee](/Tennessee), pursued his studies at [the University of the South](/University_of_the_South) and [Tulane University](/Tulane_University).
*   [Angelo Bertelli](/Angelo_Bertelli), a celebrated Notre Dame football star and [Heisman Trophy](/Heisman_Trophy) winner, was part of the program.
*   [John Robert Beyster](/John_Robert_Beyster), the visionary founder of [SAIC](/Science_Applications_International_Corporation), the Foundation for Enterprise Development, and the [Beyster Institute](/Beyster_Institute), also benefited from V-12.
*   [D. Dudley Bloom](/D._Dudley_Bloom), who commanded the flagship of the Atlantic fleet as the youngest ship commander in the U.S. Navy during World War II, was also an inventor of rolling luggage and reality-based children's toys.
*   [Harry Bonk](/Harry_Bonk), a talented [college football](/College_football) player, played [fullback](/Fullback_(American_football)) for the [University of Maryland](/University_of_Maryland,_College_Park) and later at [Dartmouth College](/Dartmouth_College) and [Bucknell University](/Bucknell_University).
*   [Frederick C. Branch](/Frederick_C._Branch), the first [African American](/African_American) officer in the [United States Marine Corps](/United_States_Marine_Corps), was a V-12 participant from [Purdue University](/Purdue_University).
